\pard\f0\fs28 The hybrid between{\b  2} and {\b 3} ({\i S.} ×{\i  rubens} Schrank) is probably the most frequent of all {\i Salix} hybrids. It often resembles 2, from which it differs, {\i inter alia,} in the sericeous pubescence of the young leaves, and the narrower, more gradually tapering leaves. It is commoner and more widespread than pure{\i  S. fragilis} and more frequently cultivated.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Several derivatives of this hybrid, some of them of garden origin, are naturalized in Britain. They are distinguished from each other chiefly by leaf-characters and by the length of the catkins and ovaries. One of them, {\i S.} ×{\i  rubens} nothovar.{\i  basfordiana} (Scaling ex Salter) Meikle, is readily identified by its glossy, orange-yellow or sometimes reddish twigs, bright green tapering leaves 9-15 × 1·5-2 cm, with finely but sharply serrate margins, long, usually drooping catkins 5-12 cm, and ovary subsessile or shortly pedicellate, exceeding the sparsely hairy bract.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  {\b S. excelsa} S.G. Gmelin,{\i  Reise Russl. }{\b 3:} 308 (1774), is very like {\b 2} ×{\b  3} but has stouter catkins, and wider, often slightly brownish, unbearded bracts.
\par

