\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp. {\b alba} : Twigs brown or yellowish-brown, erect. Leaves covered on both surfaces with appressed, silky hairs, the upper surface more or less glabrescent. Ovary subsessile. {\i Throughout most of the range of the species}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b b}) Subsp. {\b caerulea} (Sm.) Rech. fil.,{\i  Österr. Bot. Zeitschr.}{\b  110:} 338 (1963) ({\i S. caerulea} Sm.): Twigs brown or grey, erect. Leaves bluish-green, somewhat larger, soon becoming more glabrous, more conspicuously toothed than in subsp. ({\b a}).{\i  Frequently planted in Britain (where it is used in the manufacture of cricket-bats) and perhaps elsewhere, and occasionally naturalized}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b c}) Subsp. {\b vitellina} (L.) Arcangeli,{\i  Comp. Fl. Ital.} 626 (1882): Twigs bright yellow or orange, thin, sometimes pendent. Leaves paler green and indumentum less dense than in subsp. ({\b a}). Catkin-scales somewhat longer than in subsp. ({\b a}). {\i Frequently planted}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b d}) Subsp.{\b  micans }(N.J. Andersson) Rech. fil., {\i loc. cit.} (1963) ({\i S. micans} N.J. Andersson): Like subsp. (a) but leaves with very long, persistent hairs on both surfaces, therefore very shiny; ovary distinctly pedicellate.{\i  Greece}. ({\i Caucasus}.)
